I'm seeing some problems with the layout directive. It allows you to specify a pipe-separated list of "operations"

Here's the starting point:

alias chrome 'Google Chrome'
alias irc 'Colloquy'
alias skype 'Skype'
alias term 'Terminal'

alias cl layout ChatLayout
alias tl layout TerminalLayout

${cl} ${chrome}:IGNORE_FAIL,REPEAT corner top-right resize:screenSizeX_2/3;screenSizeY 0
${cl} ${irc}:IGNORE_FAIL,REPEAT corner top-left resize:screenSizeX/3;screenSizeY/3 0
${cl} ${skype}:IGNORE_FAIL,REPEAT corner bottom-left x resize:screenSizeX/3;screenSizeY_2/3 0
${cl} BEFORE show ${chrome}
${cl} AFTER hide all-but:${chrome} 
bind 1:cmd;alt chain ${cl} 

${tl} ${term}:IGNORE_FAIL,REPEAT move screenOriginX;screenOriginY screenSizeX;screenSizeY 0
${tl} BEFORE show ${term} 
${tl} AFTER hide all-but:${term}
bind 2:cmd;alt ${tl}

At this point, both "cl" and "tl" are very similar. However, when i activate the "cl" layout, I also want my skype and irc apps to appear on the screen. 

So my first idea would be to append a "show" command to the AFTER clause of "cl", similar to the example for the layout directive.

${cl} AFTER hide all-but:${chrome} | show ${irc},${skype}

However, this does not show irc or skype. Adding a second AFTER clause does the trick
${cl} AFTER show ${irc},${skype}

This tripped me up, might be good to improve the documentation here, or maybe even have slate emit a warning when its discarding input or something.

