On Dec 7, 2012, at 7:14 AM, "Alex Morega" <notifications@github.com<mailto:notifications@github.com>> wrote:

In JavaScript there's a nice way to write event handlers declaratively. Syntax borrowed from Backbonehttp://backbonejs.org/#View-delegateEvents.

events = {
    'e:cmd,shift': function(evt) {
        slate.getCurrentWindow().move(10, 10);
        slate.showHints("why does this looks forced?");
    },
    'esc:cmd': 'hint',
    'esc:ctrl': 'grid'
};

So you have a big dictionary, with keys similar to the bindings in the current config format. Values are either functions (will be called) or strings (can be interpreted as commands of some sort).

